🤖 Introduction to AI Tools for Genealogists

Lesson 1 - Getting Started with Artificial Intelligence Research Assistants

Goal: Understand what AI tools are and how to get started using them for genealogical research
Duration: 25-30 minutes
Prerequisites: Basic computer literacy and internet access
What You'll Learn: AI tool basics, account setup, interface navigation, and first interactions

What Are AI Tools and Why Should Genealogists Care?

Artificial Intelligence (AI) tools are sophisticated computer programs that can understand human language and provide intelligent responses. Think of them as highly knowledgeable research assistants available 24/7, capable of helping with various genealogical tasks from analyzing historical documents to suggesting research strategies.



For genealogists, AI tools can serve as research companions that help you:

  • Analyze historical context - Understanding the world your ancestors lived in
  • Develop research strategies - Finding new approaches when you hit brick walls
  • Interpret old documents - Getting help with handwriting, language, or historical context
  • Organize information - Structuring your findings and creating reports
  • Generate hypotheses - Exploring possible explanations for gaps in your family history
Real Example: Instead of spending hours researching 19th-century German naming conventions, you could ask an AI tool: "What were common naming patterns for German families in Bavaria during the 1850s?" and get immediate, detailed information to guide your research.

Other Tools

Large Language Models (LLMs) are a type of artificial intelligence that can understand and generate human-like text based on the immense amount of data they were trained on. Chatbots like ChatGPT and Claude are applications built on top of these models, simulating conversations with users. These powerful AI tools are now commonly available to the public through web browsers and as dedicated apps for both Android and iOS devices.


Below is a screenshot of chatGPT in a browser. Note the simple layout. Red text and arrows have been added to point out the main areas for interaction."


ChatGPT Interface

ChatGPT (by OpenAI)

Access: chat.openai.com | Cost: Free tier available, Plus subscription $20/month

✅ Strengths for Genealogy

  • Excellent for historical context and analysis
  • Strong creative problem-solving for research strategies
  • Good at organizing and structuring information
  • Large knowledge base of historical events and customs

⚠️ Considerations

  • Cannot access real-time internet data (free version)
  • May occasionally generate inaccurate historical details
  • Requires fact-checking for specific claims
  • Limited ability to analyze uploaded documents (free tier)

Best for: Research strategy development, historical context, organizing findings, brainstorming approaches to difficult research problems.

Claude (by Anthropic)

Access: claude.ai | Cost: Free tier available, Pro subscription $20/month

✅ Strengths for Genealogy

  • Excellent document analysis capabilities
  • Strong reasoning and analytical skills
  • Good at handling complex, multi-part questions
  • Thoughtful and detailed responses
  • Can analyze uploaded images and documents

⚠️ Considerations

  • Sometimes overly cautious with historical claims
  • May provide very detailed responses (can be verbose)
  • Limited real-time web access

Best for: Document analysis, complex research problems, detailed historical analysis, reviewing and critiquing research methodologies.

Other Useful AI Tools

Perplexity.ai

Specialty: AI-powered search with source citations

Best for: Finding current information and getting sources for fact-checking

Microsoft Copilot

Specialty: Integrated web search with AI responses

Best for: Real-time information lookup and general research questions

Google Gemini

Specialty: Google's AI with web integration

Best for: General questions and finding Google-indexed information

Getting Started: Your First AI Interaction



Step-by-Step Setup Process

🚀 Getting Started Checklist

⚠️ Privacy Note for Genealogists: Be cautious about sharing sensitive family information or personal details of living relatives. Use hypothetical examples or focus on ancestors who lived more than 100 years ago when practicing.

🎯 Practice Exercise: Your First AI Conversation

Let's practice starting a conversation with an AI tool. Here are some beginner-friendly genealogy questions to try:

Starter Questions to Try:

  1. General: "What types of records are most useful for researching Irish immigrants to America in the 1800s?"
  2. Historical Context: "What major events were happening in Germany during the 1840s that might have caused people to emigrate?"
  3. Research Strategy: "I'm having trouble finding records for my ancestor after 1880. What are some common reasons people disappear from records?"
  4. Document Help: "What information is typically found on a World War I draft registration card?"

✅ Great! You've completed your first AI interaction!

As you continue practicing, remember:

  • AI responses are starting points for research, not final answers
  • Always verify specific facts through primary sources
  • Use AI to generate ideas and strategies, then apply traditional genealogical methods
  • Don't hesitate to ask follow-up questions for clarification

Understanding AI Responses: What to Expect

Types of Helpful Responses You'll Receive:

📋 Research Suggestions

AI tools can suggest specific record types, repositories, or search strategies you might not have considered.

🏛️ Historical Context

Understanding the social, political, and economic conditions your ancestors lived through.

📝 Analysis and Organization

Help structuring your findings, creating timelines, or organizing complex family relationships.

🤔 Alternative Hypotheses

When you're stuck, AI can suggest alternative explanations or research approaches you hadn't considered.

Important Reminder: AI tools are research assistants, not authoritative sources. Always verify important information through primary sources and established genealogical methods. Use AI to enhance, not replace, traditional research practices.

Best Practices for Genealogists Using AI

🔑 Essential Guidelines

  • Start Simple: Begin with general questions before moving to complex research problems
  • Be Specific: Provide context about time periods, locations, and what you already know
  • Fact-Check: Always verify AI suggestions through traditional genealogical sources
  • Protect Privacy: Avoid sharing personal information about living relatives
  • Iterate: Don't hesitate to ask follow-up questions or request clarification
  • Document Sources: Keep track of which AI tool gave you ideas, but rely on primary sources for documentation

Troubleshooting Common Issues

❓ If AI Responses Seem Too General:

  • Add more specific details to your question
  • Mention specific time periods and locations
  • Explain what you've already tried

❓ If AI Responses Seem Inaccurate:

  • Ask for sources or clarification
  • Cross-reference with known genealogical sources
  • Try rephrasing your question

🎯 Lesson Summary

  • AI tools are research assistants that can help with genealogical research tasks
  • Popular options include ChatGPT and Claude, each with different strengths
  • Getting started is simple - create an account and start with basic questions
  • Always verify AI suggestions through traditional genealogical methods
  • Practice makes perfect - the more you use AI tools, the better you'll become at crafting effective questions
